  "text": "Envoy's TLS certificate validation pipeline is implemented in C++ across multiple files organized in the source/common/tls directory. The architecture follows a modular design pattern with clear separation between abstract interfaces, concrete implementations, and supporting utilities.\n\n**Abstract CertValidator Interface**\nThe abstract CertValidator interface is defined in source/common/tls/cert_validator/cert_validator.h. This class provides the core contract for certificate validation with methods for adding client validation contexts (addClientValidationContext), performing certificate chain verification (doVerifyCertChain), and initializing SSL contexts (initializeSslContexts). The interface also defines ValidationResults, a structure that encapsulates the validation status (Pending, Successful, Failed) and detailed error information including TLS alerts and error messages.\n\n**DefaultCertValidator Implementation**\nThe DefaultCertValidator class in source/common/tls/cert_validator/default_validator.h and default_validator.cc implements X.509 chain verification. This implementation handles CA certificate loading, certificate revocation list (CRL) checking, and provides utility methods for certificate validation: verifyCertificate for general certificate verification, verifyCertificateHashList for SHA-256 hash pinning, and verifyCertificateSpkiList for SPKI (Subject Public Key Information) pinning. The class supports both synchronous and asynchronous validation paths.\n\n**Subject Alternative Name (SAN) Matcher**\nThe SAN matching functionality is located in source/common/tls/cert_validator/san_matcher.h and san_matcher.cc. The abstract SanMatcher interface defines the match contract, while StringSanMatcher provides concrete implementations supporting multiple SAN types: DNS names, email addresses, URI identifiers, and IP addresses. The createStringSanMatcher factory function creates appropriate SAN matchers based on configuration, including support for custom OID-based OTHERNAME fields. SAN matching supports DNS semantics for exact matches and regex/prefix matching for other patterns.\n\n**TLS Context Management**\nThe ContextImpl class in source/common/tls/context_impl.h is the central component for managing TLS contexts, certificates, and OCSP responses. It maintains a vector of TlsContext structures, each containing an SSL_CTX, certificate chain (X509), and optionally an OCSP response wrapper. The TlsContext struct includes fields for certificate chain path, OCSP response data, ECDSA capability flags, and OCSP must-staple markers. ContextImpl provides methods for creating new SSL connections, handling asynchronous certificate verification through customVerifyCallback, and managing OCSP response expiration via secondsUntilFirstOcspResponseExpires.\n\nClientContextImpl (source/common/tls/client_context_impl.h) extends ContextImpl for client-side TLS handling with SNI (Server Name Indication) support. ServerContextImpl (source/common/tls/server_context_impl.h) extends ContextImpl for server-side TLS, including OCSP stapling functionality with the OcspStapleAction enum controlling whether to staple, not staple, fail, or indicate client incapability.\n\n**OCSP Response Parsing and Stapling**\nOCSP response support is implemented in source/common/tls/ocsp/ocsp.h and ocsp.cc. The OcspResponseWrapperImpl class manages DER-encoded OCSP responses and implements the OcspResponseWrapper interface with methods for checking expiration (isExpired, secondsUntilExpiration) and accessing update windows (getThisUpdate, getNextUpdate). The implementation supports RFC 6960 BasicOcspResponse format.\n\nThe Asn1OcspUtility class in the same file provides DER parsing functions for OCSP structures: parseOcspResponse for top-level responses, parseResponseStatus for response status enumerations, parseResponseBytes for response data, parseBasicOcspResponse for BasicOcspResponse structures, parseResponseData for response data containing single certificate statuses, parseSingleResponse for individual certificate responses, and parseCertId for certificate identity structures.\n\n**ASN.1 Parsing Infrastructure**\nThe Asn1Utility class in source/common/tls/ocsp/asn1_utility.h provides generic ASN.1 DER parsing functions used by OCSP parsing, including parseOid for object identifiers, parseGeneralizedTime for timestamps, parseInteger for arbitrary-precision integers, and parseOctetString for binary data. These utilities use BoringSSL's CBS (crypto bytestring) API for safe memory management.\n\n**Certificate Validation Configuration**\nConfiguration is managed through CertificateValidationContextConfig (envoy/ssl/certificate_validation_context_config.h) and its implementation CertificateValidationContextConfigImpl. The configuration supports CA certificates, certificate revocation lists, subject alternative name matchers, certificate hash verification, and trust chain verification modes (VERIFY_TRUST_CHAIN, ACCEPT_UNTRUSTED, etc.).\n\n**Factory Pattern**\nThe CertValidatorFactory interface (source/common/tls/cert_validator/factory.h) enables pluggable certificate validator implementations. The factory uses the getCertValidatorName function to determine which validator implementation to instantiate, defaulting to \"envoy.tls.cert_validator.default\" for the DefaultCertValidator.\n\nThe pipeline integrates certificate validation with TLS handshakes through the customVerifyCallback function, which routes certificate chains through the configured validator and handles both synchronous validation results and asynchronous validation callbacks for extended validation scenarios."
}

